> Katakana vs Hiragana</span><hr size=1> Which should I learn? Which is most widely spoken? And hiragana is the one used in most Jap video games right? (I started to use hiragana, but now I'm having doubts...) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upolykarbon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Polykarbon</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/pkmini.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sensei</span><br> <font color=#336699>(1/13/01 9:16:06 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/profile.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Katakana vs Hiragana</span><hr size=1> <br>
Hirigana and Katakana are alphabets (not spoken languages) so you still only have to learn Japanese. As far as which alphabet to start with. Start with Hirigana.<br>
<br>
Hirigana is the alphabet the Japanese use to write down words that are native to them. Katakana is the alphabet they use to write down words that are foreign in origin.<br>
<br>
more info available here at the bottom of the page:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com/japan/index.htm">www.polykarbon.com/japan/index.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <p><b><i>See you, Space Cowboy...</i></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usauqs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>sauqs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br> <font color=#336699>(1/13/01 12:57:40 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Katakana vs Hiragana</span><hr size=1> Thank you. I try that. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ukenji423.showPublicProfile?language=EN>kenji423</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/21/01 8:41:18 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/kenji423us/me.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Katakana vs Hiragana</span><hr size=1> As/if you would still read this, yes, Hiragana is more useful, if you're going to use just one.  WHY?  Learn two, that's what I did, it's remarkably easy after you have one down.  Or at least just study SOME katakana off to the side if you have spare time.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwathiik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>wathiik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/21/01 11:36:18 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> actually, hiragana and katakana are not alphabets, but syllabaries. of course, the characters for &lt;n&gt; may give you the impression that the japanese syllabaries are in fact alphabets, and the border between syllabary and alphabet is certainly fuzzy - there are many alphabets, e.g. the Indic and Ethiopic ones, that are viewed as alphabets by some scholars but as syllabaries by others. <br>
<br>
what distinguishes syllabaries from alphabets is that alphabets have symbols for single sounds (e.g. k, b, d in English), whereas syllabaries have symbols that stand for a sequence of consonant + vowel - or other syllables.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ueneref.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eneref</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/22/01 6:53:22 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> Heh... now you're arguing semantics.<br>
<br>
One could just as well argue that, if programming speech software, one must break the English alphabet down into countless combination sounds... and therefore English also uses a syllabary....<br>
<br>
One could also argue that to a Japanese, ru is a distinct and discrete sound, without seaparate parts, and therefore it is part of an alphabet.<br>
<br>
<br>
As for Hiragana, Katakana... they have a one-to-one mapping of each other, so they complement each other well. Learn both... but it's sometimes easier to learn Hiragana first if you're learning the language, as there are more applicable words you'll learn in hiragana. You already KNOW the words you'll be learning in Katakana... they just look and sound funny.... *grin* <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uruney3.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Runey3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/22/01 10:04:10 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> *grin* I just find hiragana easier because it's used for furigana/rubi in manga. Nothing like seeing the same symbol over and over to finally ram it into your head. -_- Katakana always throws me though, especially trying to interpret what word they were aiming for...<br>
<br>
Oh yeah, Eneref...why do you keep saying &quot;ha&quot; instead of &quot;wa&quot;? I know it's written as &quot;ha&quot; in kana, but....well just curious. ^_^ <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upolykarbon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Polykarbon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/pkmini.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sensei</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/23/01 8:41:30 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/googiepat.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> the guy thought Hirigana and Katakana where languages..you think I'm going to go and complicate the issue by introducing the &quot;Syballaries&quot; concept? gimme a break. <p><b><i>I am Pat's Signature</i></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ueneref.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eneref</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/25/01 5:13:41 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> I saw 'ha' because that's actually the particle....<br>
<br>
It's a habit more than anything else.... I spend much of the day typing in Japanese... so I'm used to typing out 'ha' instead of using a more pronounced 'wa.'<br>
<br>
You've no idea how difficult it is to include spaces in what I'm writing.... I'm so used to hitting the space bar when I want a kanji selection, and return when I have what I need -- ignoring spacing at all other times.  Typing in Japanese is a bitch and a half.... but once you're used to it, typing in roomaji is even more so.... *grin*<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwathiik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>wathiik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/25/01 7:36:44 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> of c. you can argue that the distinction between syllabary and alphabet are too difficult to understand for some people and that there are difrnt definitions, but still, i never thought of the japanese syllabaries as alphabets. i mean, some people probably dont see the distinction between kanji, romaji and kana, but why do we make a distinction then? cause there clearly is one.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwathiik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>wathiik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/25/01 7:41:00 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: alphabets? well</span><hr size=1> i don't understand what you by mean by english sues syllabaries... of course, in real language, there is quite some allophony, but english spelling doesnt really indicate allophones, rather, it works a bit like kanji in some instances - think of rough, plough, words like these - you have to memorize the spelling of the words as units rather than the single letters. but english spelling really isn't syllabic - it would be difficult to write words like extra syllabically - in kana, it would be probably somethin like e-ku-su-tu-ra... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ueneref.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eneref</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/26/01 5:54:11 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> phonemes</span><hr size=1> It's all a matter of what we've been taught to view as the discrete phonemes. There's an accepted set we use in English, and because of that, we tend to thing of our alphabet as exactly that, an alphabet....<br>
<br>
But if we were to break things down into further-degraded syllabic chunks, we might find that the 'e' in extra is two discrete sounds together... as the x is obviously two... the t might be two sounds, a stopped one and a voiced portion, the r might be two as well, and the a could be even more...<br>
<br>
It's really a matter of how far you break the phonemes down. Phonemes, are, by definition, a single, distinct sound. But if you've ever done speech therapy with deaf people, or even something as simple as programming speech software, you know that a phoneme is NOT truly discrete... it breaks up into many distinct parts. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwathiik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>wathiik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/27/01 1:39:33 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: phonemes</span><hr size=1> i'm not sure what you're saying... you're trying to tell me that phonemes are not discrete in the sense that there is only a certain number of them in each language? sure. the problem with english spelling is that is has very little to do with phonemes, and very much with different historical orthographical traditions. EXTRA for example comes from Latin and was pronounced /ekstra<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :/ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":/"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . Modern english is quite difrnt from Latin , and it's pronounced as /ekstr@/ in english. of c english spelling is alphabetical, but it's certainly not phonemic, and in some cases - as i already mentioned - it's quite close to logography, because the shape of the word has very little or even nothing to do with its actual pronounciation.<br>
<br>
anyway, from a certain point of view, syllabaries are very difrnt from alphabets, but then again, there are (as almost evriwhere) fuzzy borders and they're both phonographic systems.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showMessage?topicID=340.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showMessage?topicID=332.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br></td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.emailToFriend?topicID=142.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.threadControl?topicID=142.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=142.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=142.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub25.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="polykarbonbbsfrm18">PK-BBS Rules and Regulations!<option value="polykarbonbbsfrm3">News and Updates<option value="polykarbonbbsfrm2">Photoshop and Art questions<option value="polykarbonbbsfrm4">General Manga Discussion<option value="polykarbonbbsfrm5">Japanese Language Help<option value="polykarbonbbsfrm23">art in progress